            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                New York&#44; June 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 87<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr.<lb/></p>
            <p>In accordance with<lb/> your request of last Tuesday&#44; I would<lb/> report the standing of the class<lb/> as follows.  Since the beginning of<lb/> the term we have taken five chapters<lb/> of &#91;Hebrew&#93; with &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; eighteen Psalms with<lb/> introduction the entire Mishnah of<lb/> Berachoth with Bertinova with the exception of the third<lb/> chapter&#44; three pages of the Gemara of Bala<lb/> Metsia&#44; in History the Judges down to<lb/> Samuel and in Grammar the reg&#45;<lb/>ular noun and regular verb com&#45;<lb/>plete.  Previously to the commencement<lb/> of regular instruction&#44; the class had<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>taken under my instruction the en&#45;<lb/>tire &#91;Hebrew&#93; and I had delivered one<lb/> lecture on the connection of the<lb/> Hebrew with the other Semitic lang&#45;<lb/>uages.  The boys may be grouped as<lb/> regard standing and scholarship as<lb/> follows.  The two Herz boys undoubtedly<lb/> head the class with Josiah first&#44; then<lb/> Simson&#44; next Levi and Rubenstein foll&#45;<lb/>owed by Cohen who would stand very<lb/> well but for his frequent absences<lb/> towards the end of the term and<lb/> after him Blankford.  Laski and<lb/> Bernstein are those who stand poorest<lb/> in the class.  I have taken occasion<lb/> to examine the &#91;Hebrew&#93; more in detail<lb/> and although it is by no means<lb/> undiff indispensable&#44; still it could<lb/> be used very satisfactorily as<lb/> a means of giving beginners their<lb/></p> 
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>first acquaintance with the Tal&#45;<lb/>mud.  Its chief advantage would<lb/> be in case of a lack of books from<lb/> which to chose but where a good lib&#45;<lb/>rary exists it could easily be <sic>distenced</sic><lb/> with.  I remain<lb/> very sincerely yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/> 439 E. 56<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
